revision.text:
'''宮島'''（みやじま、みやしま）
*日本人の[[姓]]の一つ *日本の地名の一つ **[[新潟県]][[上越市]][[板倉区]]宮島 **[[兵庫県]][[豊岡市]]宮島 *[[厳島]]の別名
{{aimai}}

{{ill|Miyajima|en}}
, located in {{ill|Hatsukaichi|en|12=draft|12=draft}}
, {{ill|Hiroshima Prefecture|en}}
. Sanki Daigongen is believed to command both great and small Tengu as retainers, using vast supernatural powers to save sentient beings. Locally, it is affectionately referred to as '''Sanki-san'''. It is said that {{ill|Itō Hirobumi|en|12=draft|12=draft}}
, Japan’s first Prime Minister, was a devout follower.
The three deities of Sanki Daigongen are: * **Tsuichō Kishin (追帳鬼神)**: A deity governing the virtue of "fortune and virtue" (福徳), with {{ill|Dainichi Nyorai|en}}
as the {{ill|honji-butsu|en|12=draft|12=draft}}
(original Buddha). * **Jibi Kishin (時眉鬼神)**: A deity overseeing the virtue of "wisdom" (知恵), with {{ill|Kokūzō Bosatsu|en}}
as the honji-butsu. Kokūzō Bosatsu is also the principal deity enshrined at {{ill|Misen Main Hall|en|12=draft|12=draft}}
. * **Mara Kishin (魔羅鬼神)**: A deity associated with the virtue of "subjugation" (降伏), with {{ill|Fudō Myōō|en}}
as the honji-butsu.
Following the {{ill|Shinbutsu Bunri|en|12=draft|12=draft}}
(the separation of Shinto and Buddhism), the deities were relocated from the original {{ill|Miyama Shrine|en}}
to the current Sanki-dō.
=== Origin === It is believed that the revered monk {{ill|Kūkai|en|12=draft|12=draft}}
(also known as Kōbō Daishi) enshrined Sanki Daigongen in 806 CE (Daido 1) when he founded Mount Misen as a sacred site.
=== Mantra === The mantra associated with Sanki Daigongen is: * '''On Aratan Nō Un Sowaka''' (オン・アラタンノウ・ウン・ソワカ).
Additionally, there are {{ill|wasan|en}}
(Buddhist hymns) praising the virtues of Sanki Daigongen. == See Also == * {{ill|List of Buddhas|en|12=draft|12=draft}}
* {{ill|Gongen|en}}
* {{ill|Daitengu|en|12=draft|12=draft}}
* {{ill|Mountain worship|en}}
* {{ill|Mitaki-dera|en|12=draft|12=draft}}
* {{ill|Guhin|en}}
