, located in {{ill|Hatsukaichi|en|12=draft}}

, {{ill|Hiroshima Prefecture|en}}

. Sanki Daigongen is believed to command both great and small Tengu as retainers, using vast supernatural powers to save sentient beings. Locally, it is affectionately referred to as '''Sanki-san'''. It is said that {{ill|Itō Hirobumi|en|12=draft}}

, Japan’s first Prime Minister, was a devout follower.

The three deities of Sanki Daigongen are:
* **Tsuichō Kishin (追帳鬼神)**: A deity governing the virtue of "fortune and virtue" (福徳), with {{ill|Dainichi Nyorai|en}}

 as the {{ill|honji-butsu|en|12=draft}}

 (original Buddha).
* **Jibi Kishin (時眉鬼神)**: A deity overseeing the virtue of "wisdom" (知恵), with {{ill|Kokūzō Bosatsu|en}}

 as the honji-butsu. Kokūzō Bosatsu is also the principal deity enshrined at {{ill|Misen Main Hall|en|12=draft}}

.
* **Mara Kishin (魔羅鬼神)**: A deity associated with the virtue of "subjugation" (降伏), with {{ill|Fudō Myōō|en}}

 as the honji-butsu.

Following the {{ill|Shinbutsu Bunri|en|12=draft}}

 (the separation of Shinto and Buddhism), the deities were relocated from the original {{ill|Miyama Shrine|en}}

 to the current Sanki-dō.

=== Origin ===
It is believed that the revered monk {{ill|Kūkai|en|12=draft}}

