<!--Miyajima--><!--Miyajima--><!--Miyajima--><!--Miyajima--><!--Miyajima--><!--Miyajima--><!--Miyajima--><!--Miyajima--><!--Miyajima--><!--Miyajima--><!--Miyajima--><!--Miyajima--><!--Miyajima--><!--Miyajima--><!--Miyajima--><!--Miyajima--><!--Miyajima--><!--Miyajima--><!--Miyajima-->

{{ill|Miyajima|en|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Miyajima|qq=}}

, located in {{ill|Hatsukaichi|en|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Hatsukaichi|qq=}}

, {{ill|Hiroshima Prefecture|en|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Hiroshima Prefecture|qq=}}

. Sanki Daigongen is believed to command both great and small Tengu as retainers, using vast supernatural powers to save sentient beings. Locally, it is affectionately referred to as '''Sanki-san'''. It is said that {{ill|Itō Hirobumi|en|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Itō Hirobumi|qq=}}

, Japan’s first Prime Minister, was a devout follower.

The three deities of Sanki Daigongen are:
* **Tsuichō Kishin (追帳鬼神)**: A deity governing the virtue of "fortune and virtue" (福徳), with {{ill|Dainichi Nyorai|en|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Dainichi Nyorai|qq=}}

 as the {{ill|honji-butsu|en|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/honji-butsu|qq=}}

 (original Buddha).
* **Jibi Kishin (時眉鬼神)**: A deity overseeing the virtue of "wisdom" (知恵), with {{ill|Kokūzō Bosatsu|en|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Kokūzō Bosatsu|qq=}}

 as the honji-butsu. Kokūzō Bosatsu is also the principal deity enshrined at {{ill|Misen Main Hall|en|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Misen Main Hall|qq=}}

.
* **Mara Kishin (魔羅鬼神)**: A deity associated with the virtue of "subjugation" (降伏), with {{ill|Fudō Myōō|en|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Fudō Myōō|qq=}}

 as the honji-butsu.

Following the {{ill|Shinbutsu Bunri|en|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Shinbutsu Bunri|qq=}}

 (the separation of Shinto and Buddhism), the deities were relocated from the original {{ill|Miyama Shrine|en|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Miyama Shrine|qq=}}

 to the current Sanki-dō.

=== Origin ===
It is believed that the revered monk {{ill|Kūkai|en|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Kūkai|qq=}}

 (also known as Kōbō Daishi) enshrined Sanki Daigongen in 806 CE (Daido 1) when he founded Mount Misen as a sacred site.

=== Mantra ===
The mantra associated with Sanki Daigongen is:
* '''On Aratan Nō Un Sowaka''' (オン・アラタンノウ・ウン・ソワカ).

Additionally, there are {{ill|wasan|en|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/wasan|qq=}}

 (Buddhist hymns) praising the virtues of Sanki Daigongen.
